error.403: The client does not have access rights to the content so the server is rejecting the response.
error.404:
The server cannot find the requested resource. 
This response code is perhaps the most famous because of how often it happens across the web.
error.500: The server has encountered a situation that it does not know how to handle.
error.401:
Although the HTTP standard specifies "unauthorized", semantically this response means "unauthenticated". 
That is, the client must authenticate itself to obtain the requested response.
error.422: The request is well formed but unable to be followed due to semantic errors.
